AFL | Ulta Beauty Inc (Christopher Horvers, CFA) (ULTA, OW, PT \(\) 600.00\$
Upward Revisions Set to Continue; Reiterate Overweight/Analyst Focus List; Key Mgmt Takes

PM's take: one of the best upward revision momentum stories in our coverage as the truth sets ULTA free. ULTA produced a very high quality beat (Figure 1) with comps well- ahead of our raised- into- the- print forecast and strong flow- through to the bottom- line (along with merchandise margin expansion). The company gained share for the second consecutive qtr as Sephora at KSS headwinds fade (Figure 9) while the category accelerated on the prestige side (+MSD from +LSD with mass holding at +LSD).
AFL | Ollie's Bargain Outlet Holdings (Matthew R. Boss, CPA) (OLLI, OW, PT \(\) 159.00\$

OLLI reported 2Q adj. EPS- of \(\) 0.99\(above Street\) \ \(0.92\) comprised of \(+5.0\%\) same- store sales or a \(10.8\%\) 2- year stack ( \(>\) Street at \(+1.7\%\) ) and gross margin expansion of \(+206\) bps Y/Y to \(39.9\%\) (above Street at \(39.1\%\) ) translating to \(21\%\) gross profit dollar growth (doubling the model's \(\sim 10\%\) TTM average). Looking ahead, management raised the FY25 EPS outlook to \(\) 3.76- 3.84\(vs.\) \ \(3.86 - 3.75\) prior and Street \(\) 3.76\(based on +3.0 - 3.5\% S\) SS (vs \(+1.4 - 2.2\%\) prior), 85 net new stores ( \(= 15\%\) unit growth vs. \(\) 2\(prior), gross margin\) \sim 40.3\% \(>historical\) \log / \mathrm{vs.} \(prior\) \sim 40.0\% \(), and 11.2\% margin at the midpoint (vs 11.0- 11.2\% prior guide and Street at 11.2\%.\)
The Gap, Inc. (Matthew R. Boss, CPA) (GAP, OW, PT \(\) 32.00\$ CFO- Follow- Up Takes & Model Math = Buying Opportunity; Overweight 4 Key Incremental CFO Follow- Up Takeaways:

(1) July Comp Inflection To Close 2Q ... Breaking down the cadence of 2Q's \(+1.0\%\) comp growth, CFO O'Connell noted May/June started slow due to unfavorably cold/wet weather weighing on core seasonal merchandise ( \(= -\) Flat May/June consolidated SSS by our work), relative to a sharp acceleration to mid-single-digit comps in July on our estimates, coinciding w the Fall product drop and back-to-school assortment flowed through to stores.

Dell executed on better AI server delivery to customers \(\) 8.2\(bn of revenue vs. JPM of\) \ \(7.2\) bn) as well as booked robust incremental orders \(\) 5.6\(bn) in the quarter to support a strong backlog, which is proving instrumental in the raise to the full - year outlook for revenues by about\) \ \(4\) bn at the mid- point from \(\) 103\(bn to\) \ \(107\) bn. At the same time however, the execution to keep up with customer demand on AI servers was done at the expense of margins with supply chain inefficiencies, including expedite costs, further pressuring ISG margins beyond the already envisioned pressure from competitive AI server deals to win business with concentrated customers, leading to only a muted -\) \ \(85\) mn increase in guidance for Operating Income for the fullyear.
Despite higher tariffs, India continues to buy Russian crude at reduced levels, a trend likely to persist until a trade deal is finalized and Russia maintains discounts

Russia has successfully redirected the 0.5 mbd drop in Indian exports but is unlikely to offer discounts beyond the current \(\) 2.60\(/bbl, preferring to cut production over providing the deep discounts seen in 2022\)

Daily Economic Briefing (Maia G Crook)

The second release of US 2Q25 GDP delivered an upward revision to a \(3.3\%\) ar gain. The material upward revision to domestic final sales growth (from \(1.1\%\) ar to \(1.6\%\) ar) was concentrated in nonresidential business investment, where every category was revised up. The slowing in equipment spending gains from 1Q25 has moderated, with gains now at a \(7.4\%\) ar. Intellectual property product spending was notably weak last year, rising just \(2.7\%\) , but with today's upward revision it is now up a \(9.3\%\) ar in 1H25. This rebound can principally be attributed to a \(22\%\) ar rise in software spending in 1H25, which likely in part reflects earnings from selling AI software services.
